{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18483"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76086"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7491"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26262"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76086"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe round window is one of two membrane-covered openings between the middle and inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the round window?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allows pressure relief for cochlear fluid movements","Conducts sound waves to the inner ear","Connects the middle ear to mastoid air cells","Produces endolymph fluid","Equalises middle ear pressure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eallows pressure relief for cochlear fluid movements\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the round window (Image). When the stapes footplate pushes inward at the oval window, it creates pressure waves in the cochlear fluid. The round window membrane bulges outward to accommodate this pressure change, allowing proper movement of cochlear fluids and the basilar membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConducts sound waves to the inner ear\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of the oval window and stapes footplate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects the middle ear to mastoid air cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is achieved through the aditus ad antrum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces endolymph fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by the stria vascularis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqualises middle ear pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of the auditory (Eustachian) tube\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWithout the flexible round window membrane, cochlear fluid would be incompressible and sound transmission would be impaired. The round window thus serves as a pressure relief valve for the cochlear system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The round window is a membrane-covered opening in the medial wall of the middle ear that allows pressure changes to dissipate from the inner ear.","The round window is located below and behind the oval window in the middle ear cavity.","The round window membrane bulges outward when the stapes pushes inward, allowing proper sound wave transmission through the cochlea."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAnatomy of Human Ear with Cochlear Frequency Mapping\u201d by Inductiveload is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 2.5 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Anatomy_of_Human_Ear_with_Cochlear_Frequency_Mapping.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61587"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21394"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21394"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iaciOoEHhB7IHneuSpMxcVeDFn6JWz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iaciOoEHhB7IHneuSpMxcVeDFn6JWz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":493}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61587"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T01:35:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T01:37:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76086"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{